{{Infobox venue | name = Alsterdorfer Sporthalle | nickname = | fullname = | former names = Sporthalle Hamburg {{small|(1968-84)}} | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Hh-alsterdorfersporthalle.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_alt = | caption = Exterior of venue (c.2006) | address = Krochmannstraße 55 | location = [[Alsterdorf]], [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]] | coordinates = {{coord|53|36|10|N|10|00|07|E|display=inline,title|region:DE_type:landmark_source:dewiki}} | publictransit = {{ÖPNV Hamburg|U1|12}} [[Lattenkamp (Hamburg U-Bahn station)|Lattenkamp (Sporthalle)]] | type = | built = | opened = 1968 | owner = Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = Yes | cost = | architect = Herbert Schmedje<ref>[http://www.heinze.de/architekturobjekt/alsterdorfer-sporthalle/12622458 Alsterdorfer Sporthalle], ''heinze.de'', Retrieved 18 November 2015</ref> | structural engineer = | main_contractors = | seating_type = hard seats | capacity = 7,000 | suites = | dimensions = | field_shape = | volume = | tenants = [[HSV Hamburg]] | website = {{URL|hamburg-sporthalle.de}} }} '''Alsterdorfer Sporthalle'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mopo.de/hamburg/ausgehen/musik---partys/alsterdorfer-sporthalle-auf-ein-letztes-taenzchen-mit-bosse-25256690 |language=German |trans-title=Alsterdorfer Sporthalle: On a last dance with bosses |title=Alsterdorfer Sporthalle: Auf ein letztes Tänzchen mit Bosse |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 December 2016 |website=[[Hamburger Morgenpost]] |publisher=[[M. DuMont Schauberg]] |accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> (originally known as the '''Sporthalle Hamburg''') is an indoor [[arena]] in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]. The arena holds up to 7,000 people with 4,200 seats. It opened in 1968 and is located in the city's quarter of [[Winterhude]].
[[File:Grüne Parteitag Sporthalle Hamburg - Fisheye.jpg|thumbnail|left|Inside of the Sporthalle (2014)]] It hosts mainly indoor sporting events ([[HSV Handball]]), pop & rock concerts and trade shows. The [[1978 World Fencing Championships]] were held here. In July 2010, all matches of the [[FIBA Under-17 World Championship 2010]] were played in this hall. In 11 May 2001, Irish vocal pop band [[Westlife]] held a concert for their [[Where Dreams Come True Tour]] supporting their album [[Coast to Coast (Westlife album)|Coast to Coast]]. From 2012 until 2014 it also played host to the annual [[PDC World Cup of Darts]].
